# Parallel Project Rule — Zero-Burden Invariant

## Core Product Rule

Rotation is for distributing unavoidable inconvenience, not for creating inconvenience when a fully comfortable shared time already exists.

If any valid zero-burden candidate exists, no non-zero-burden candidate may win.

Rotation exists to distribute unavoidable inconvenience.
It must never create inconvenience when a fully comfortable shared time already exists.

A valid zero-burden candidate means:
- passes all hard no-time constraints
- all participants are within working hours
- total burden = 0
- max individual burden = 0

This is a strict product invariant, not a preference.

---

## Required Scheduler Behavior

### 1. Zero-burden-first invariant
Before any fairness balancing, beam ranking, topK pruning, greedy comparison, anchor preference, fallback search, or forced search can select a burden-producing time, the scheduler must first preserve and prioritize the zero-burden candidate set.

If one or more valid zero-burden candidates exist:
- final selection must come only from that zero-burden subset
- fairness may only be used as a deterministic tie-breaker within that zero-burden subset
- anchor/base-time preference may only be used as a deterministic tie-breaker within that zero-burden subset
- non-zero-burden candidates must not be allowed to win

### 2. Inconvenience rotation starts only when zero-burden is impossible
Only when there are no valid zero-burden candidates may the scheduler begin distributing inconvenience.

### 3. Hard boundaries remain unchanged
Hard no-time boundaries remain the only hard scheduling constraint.
This rule does not weaken or reinterpret hard boundaries.

### 4. Working hours remain soft globally, but zero-burden is a protected class
Working hours are still modeled as soft constraints in general scoring.
However, when a candidate keeps all members within working hours and creates zero burden for all members, that candidate class has strict priority over all burden-producing candidates.

### 5. Determinism remains mandatory
Given identical inputs, the scheduler must return identical outputs.
Tie-breaking inside the zero-burden subset must remain deterministic.

---

## Candidate Preservation Rule

No candidate ordering, sorting, slicing, beam pruning, or fallback filtering step may eliminate zero-burden candidates before burden-aware comparison is complete.

This applies to:
- main search
- beam search
- fallback beam search
- forced search
- greedy selection
- anchor mode
- debug verification search
- any helper that reorders candidates before final comparison

If a path can remove or disadvantage zero-burden candidates before they are compared against non-zero-burden candidates, that is a blocking algorithm bug.

---

## Anchor / Base Time Rule

Anchor or base-time preference is subordinate to zero-burden priority.

This means:
- anchor proximity may not rank a non-zero-burden candidate above a zero-burden candidate
- in anchor mode, ordering must still preserve zero-burden-first behavior
- anchor preference may only decide ordering within the zero-burden subset or within the non-zero subset after zero-burden handling is complete

---

## Equity / Fairness Adjustment Rule

Equity balancing may not convert a zero-burden candidate into a loser against a non-zero-burden candidate.

This means:
- fairness-adjusted scoring must not cause a burden-producing candidate to beat a valid zero-burden candidate
- if a zero-burden candidate exists, fairness adjustment may only break ties within the zero-burden subset
- zero-burden must remain a protected priority state throughout scoring

---

## Beam / TopK Rule

Any beam or topK search must preserve zero-burden candidates.

This means:
- topK slicing may only happen after zero-burden-safe ordering
- if zero-burden candidates exist, they must survive into the compared subset
- no natural UTC ordering, base-time ordering, or other pre-sort may cause zero-burden candidates to be sliced away

If topK can exclude zero-burden candidates before evaluation, that path is invalid.

---

## Greedy Selection Rule

Any greedy week-by-week selection path must obey the same invariant.

This means:
- if zero-burden candidates exist for the current week and pass all relevant constraints, selection must be restricted to those zero-burden candidates
- fairness-adjusted or composite scoring may only compare candidates inside that zero-burden subset
- non-zero-burden candidates must not be selected while valid zero-burden candidates exist

---

## UI / Explanation Rule

If zero-burden overlap exists, the product must reflect that truth.

### Required behavior:
- selected schedule must come from a real computed zero-burden candidate
- explanation must not imply unavoidable sacrifice when none exists
- “other equally comfortable options” must use real computed alternatives, never mock/static/demo/dead data

### Suggestion chip requirements:
- derived from real scheduler candidates
- respect IANA timezones
- respect DST
- respect duration
- respect hard no-times
- respect working hours
- exclude currently selected time
- deterministic
- deduplicated
- limited to a small useful count

---

## Mandatory Audit Targets

Any change touching scheduling must explicitly audit all of the following:

1. Candidate generation
2. Hard-valid filtering
3. Candidate ordering helpers
4. Beam/topK pruning
5. Greedy selection paths
6. Fairness/equity adjustment functions
7. Anchor/base-time ordering
8. Fallback/forced search paths
9. Debug verification search parity
10. UI suggestion data source

---

## Mandatory Regression Scenarios

### Scenario A — Full shared overlap exists
If a team has one or more zero-burden shared times, final output must come from that set.

### Scenario B — No zero-burden overlap exists
If no zero-burden option exists, fairness rotation may distribute inconvenience.

### Scenario C — Hard boundary conflict
No candidate may violate hard no-times even if it would otherwise reduce burden.

### Scenario D — Anchor mode with zero-burden options
Base-time preference must not override zero-burden priority.

### Scenario E — Greedy path parity
Greedy selection must obey the same zero-burden-first invariant as beam search.

### Scenario F — Fallback / forced path parity
Fallback and forced paths must preserve zero-burden-first behavior.

### Scenario G — DST-sensitive overlap
Zero-burden detection must still work correctly across DST changes using IANA timezones.

### Scenario H — Explanation / UI parity
The explanation and suggestion chips must reflect real computed schedule data.

---

## Change Control

When modifying scheduling logic:
- make the smallest safe localized change
- do not refactor unrelated fairness or rotation logic
- do not rename stable tested functions unless necessary
- identify every path where candidates are sorted, sliced, or re-scored
- document before/after behavior
- verify determinism after changes
- verify no hard-boundary regression
- verify zero-burden-first invariant in all affected paths

Any change that allows a non-zero-burden candidate to win while a valid zero-burden candidate exists is a blocking regression.
